AGI - Great expectation in North America > for a total solar eclipse > that will turn the evening of 8 April the day at night in some parts of Mexico, the United States and Canada > . In fact, it is expected that the Moon fully covers the luminous disc of the Sun in a wide area of the continent: According to Nasa more than 31 million Americans will be able to see the total eclipse, being in the affected area, weather conditions allowing. The event should be visible first on the west coast of Mexico>. It will start at 17.42 (Italian time) and will end at about 22.52. He'll reach his climax at 20.17. The route will pass through 15 American states, > from Texas to Maine, before ending its trip to eastern Canada, in all will be 115 miles wide and will cover almost 32 million Americans, with another 150 million living within 200 miles from the line. The most distant ones will still enjoy a partial eclipse.<br> <br> - INCOGNITA METEO><br> There is a "incognita meteo" factor, explains Cristian Ferradas, researcher at the NASA Goddard Space Flight Center geospatial physics laboratory: "If the sky is not serene, we could see changes in the temperature and behaviour of animals while the phenomenon lasts, but we will not see the visual effect of the 100% eclipse." According to the US weather service, "optimal observation conditions are unlikely due to the expected cloud. Today there will be high and thin clouds" and it is also expected that these increases right at the time of the eclipse. But, according to the expert, beyond the "view show" that represents for the general public, this eclipse is interesting from the scientific point of view to study relevant aspects related to the astro. "The outer layer of the solar atmosphere, called a crown, usually cannot be seen directly, so this eclipse represents a unique search opportunity," says the agency's space flight center scientist in the American city of Greenbelt (Maryland). NASA will take advantage of the opportunity to directly analyze this crown, without the need for intervention of large telescopes and specialized tools used to create artificial eclipses.

<div </div

- CELEBRATIONS AND THE 'SPECIAL POWER' OF ECLISSI >
"Eclipses have special power," said NASA administrator Bill Nelson. "They make people feel a kind of reverence for the beauty of our universe," he added. In the territories where you can observe the totality of the eclipse, festivals, observation parties and even a mass wedding are planned, transforming for some moments the day at night. For weeks, the U.S. authorities have worked out safety instructions, in particular the need to use special glasses to look at the Sun > and avoid eye damage.
&nbsp;
The Nasa will broadcast a live video of three hours from various locations, with telescope images and expert comments. Among the emblematic places where the eclipse will be visible are the Niagara Falls, where the show promises to be great. On the Canadian side, the region even declared the "emergency state" to better cope with the influx of visitors. Also in Texas, > in the south of the United States, with different locations organized to accommodate tourists and campers, the local authorities declared the state of emergency due to the huge expected influx.
&nbsp;

&nbsp;
- TURISMO 'STELLARE'><br> Many regions should also benefit from the arrival of tourists. "We have people from all 50 states, including Alaska and Hawaii. There are tourists from the Netherlands, Finland, Germany, Israel, New Zealand," says Jennyth Peterson, manager of the Stonehenge II Park in Ingram, Texas, where there is a replica of England's prehistoric structure. "This is our third solar eclipse," said AFP Jim Saltigerald, 62, who was present with his wife and two children. "We are all praying and hoping to rest well in the clouds and see it." In Burlington, in the American state of Vermont, the population could double in one day, according to local authorities. In Russellville, in Arkansas, 300 couples will exchange wedding vows in an imposing wedding ceremony. "A total eclipse of the heart", the organizers say, evoking the famous song by Bonnie Tyler (Total Eclipse of Love, popularized in Spanish by Lissette lvarez).
&nbsp;
Many hotels have been full for months, with exorbitant prices, and there are traffic jams, as during the last total eclipse in the United States, in 2017. For the occasion many schools will close or allow students to leave early. The eclipse can also be admired from above: some airlines have scheduled flights along the path of darkness, whose tickets are already exhausted. Astronauts on board the International Space Station will also observe the phenomenon, but they will see the shadow of the Moon moving on the Earth's surface.
&nbsp;
- NASA's 'RILASCI'
The event is also scientific. The Nasa will launch three small probe rockets before, during and immediately after the eclipse from Virginia, in the eastern part of the United States. The goal: to measure the changes caused by darkness at the top of the Earth's atmosphere, the ionosphere, through which most communication signals pass. The solar crown, the outer layer of the Sun's atmosphere, becomes particularly visible during an eclipse. It will be observed carefully: this is where the sun shines. Researchers are particularly excited that the Sun is near the peak of its 11-year cycle. The next total eclipse visible in the United States (excluding Alaska) will take place in 2044.
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
